{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1c44add9-7d30-4dc4-8345-777a5a9a0ede","content":"Use the `--filter` option:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~ReportExporterTests\"\n```\n\nOr more explicitly by class name:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --filter \"ClassName=ReportExporterTests\"\n```\n\nThe `~` operator means \"contains\", so the first form matches any fully qualified name containing \"ReportExporterTests\". The second form does an exact match on the class name (without namespace).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e31ae0f9-e8d9-4822-82b3-6186365a38b0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to know how to run only a specific test class using `dotnet test`. This is a straightforward question about dotnet CLI usage - I don't need to explore the codebase for this.\n\nThe command to run a specific test class with `dotnet test` is:\n\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~ReportExporterTests\"\n```\n\nor\n\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"ClassName=ReportExporterTests\"\n```\n\nLet me give a concise answer.","outputTokens":246,"requestId":"BC3B:3595D9:2DE08A:34F11D:69FA9552"},"id":"2e67ad6e-8186-4e3d-bd1f-e59b34f22249","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:11:52.788Z","parentId":"172de5f9-3a2d-4509-968e-5288140db327"}
